     1→# Feature: Edit and Delete Task
     2→
     3→## Feature Description
     4→Enhance the task card interface by adding interactive icons that allow users to edit and delete existing tasks. A pencil icon will enable users to modify task details through the same creation modal (repurposed with edit capabilities), while a trash can icon will allow users to delete tasks after confirming their intent. This feature transforms the weekly planner from a create-only system into a full CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) task management application.
     5→
     6→## User Story
     7→As a weekly planner user
     8→I want to edit and delete tasks that I've already created
     9→So that I can correct mistakes, update task details as plans change, and remove tasks that are no longer relevant
    10→
    11→## Problem Statement
    12→The current weekly planner allows users to create and view tasks but provides no mechanism to modify or remove them after creation. Users who need to update task details (change date, title, description, or type) or delete obsolete tasks have no way to do so, making the application impractical for real-world task management where changes and corrections are common.
    13→
    14→## Solution Statement
    15→Add two action icons to each task card: a pencil icon for editing and a trash can icon for deletion. Clicking the pencil icon will open the existing "Add New Task" modal in edit mode, pre-populated with the task's current data, allowing users to modify any field and save changes via the existing PATCH /api/tasks/:id endpoint. Clicking the trash can icon will display a confirmation dialog to prevent accidental deletions, and upon confirmation, will delete the task via the existing DELETE /api/tasks/:id endpoint. Both operations will refresh the task list to reflect the changes immediately.
    16→
    17→## Relevant Files
    18→Use these files to implement the feature:
    19→
    20→### Frontend Files
    21→- `app/client/src/app/app.component.ts` - Main component logic (lines 1-167)
    22→  - Add property to track edit mode state (`isEditMode: boolean`, `editingTaskId: number | null`)
    23→  - Create `openEditModal(task: Task)` method to populate form with task data and set edit mode
    24→  - Modify `openModal()` method to handle both create and edit modes
    25→  - Modify `onSubmit()` method to detect edit mode and call appropriate service method
    26→  - Create `confirmDelete(task: Task)` method to show confirmation and handle deletion
    27→  - Add `updateTask()` method to call service and refresh tasks on success
    28→  - Add `deleteTask()` method to call service and refresh tasks on success
    29→  - Update `closeModal()` to reset edit mode state
    30→
    31→- `app/client/src/app/app.component.html` - Main component template (lines 1-103)
    32→  - Add action icons container within each task card (pencil and trash can)
    33→  - Add click handlers for edit and delete icons
    34→  - Modify modal header to display "Edit Task" when in edit mode vs "Add New Task"
    35→  - Modify submit button text to display "Update Task" when in edit mode vs "Create Task"
    36→  - Add confirmation dialog structure for delete confirmation (overlay with message and buttons)
    37→
    38→- `app/client/src/app/app.component.css` - Component styling (lines 1-386)
    39→  - Add styles for task action icons container (`.task-actions`)
    40→  - Add styles for individual action icons (`.action-icon`, `.edit-icon`, `.delete-icon`)
    41→  - Add hover effects and transitions for action icons
    42→  - Add styles for delete confirmation dialog (`.confirm-dialog`, `.confirm-dialog-content`)
    43→  - Add styles for confirmation dialog buttons
    44→  - Ensure icons are properly positioned within task cards
    45→  - Add responsive considerations for icon sizing on smaller screens
    46→
    47→- `app/client/src/app/services/task.service.ts` - HTTP service for task operations (lines 1-40)
    48→  - Add `updateTask(id: number, task: Partial<Task>): Observable<Task>` method to PATCH updates to the API
    49→  - Add `deleteTask(id: number): Observable<void>` method to DELETE tasks via the API
    50→  - Use consistent error handling with existing methods
    51→
    52→- `app/client/src/app/models/task.model.ts` - TypeScript task interfaces (lines 1-19)
    53→  - No changes needed - existing Task interface already includes id field required for edit/delete operations
    54→
    55→### Backend Files
    56→- `app/server/routers/tasks.py` - API endpoints (lines 1-106)
    57→  - No changes needed - PATCH /api/tasks/:id endpoint already exists (lines 46-77)
    58→  - No changes needed - DELETE /api/tasks/:id endpoint already exists (lines 79-106)
    59→
    60→- `app/server/crud.py` - Database operations (lines 1-133)
    61→  - No changes needed - update_task() function already exists (lines 76-125)
    62→  - No changes needed - delete_task() function already exists (lines 127-133)
    63→
    64→- `app/server/tests/test_api.py` - API endpoint tests
    65→  - Add test for updating task via frontend service method
    66→  - Add test for deleting task via frontend service method
    67→  - Verify edit and delete operations don't create regressions
    68→
    69→### New Files
    70→None required - all functionality can be implemented using existing files and endpoints
    71→
    72→## Implementation Plan
    73→
    74→### Phase 1: Foundation - Service Layer Updates
    75→Update the TaskService to support edit and delete operations by adding methods that call the existing backend PATCH and DELETE endpoints. This provides the foundation for the UI components to interact with the API.
    76→
    77→- Add updateTask() method to TaskService for PATCH requests
    78→- Add deleteTask() method to TaskService for DELETE requests
    79→- Ensure error handling is consistent with existing service methods
    80→
    81→### Phase 2: Core Implementation - Edit Functionality
    82→Implement the edit feature by adding a pencil icon to task cards and modifying the modal to support both create and edit modes. The modal will pre-populate with existing task data when editing and submit updates to the PATCH endpoint.
    83→
    84→- Add edit icon to task cards with click handler
    85→- Create edit mode state management in component
    86→- Implement openEditModal() method to populate form with task data
    87→- Modify onSubmit() to detect edit mode and call updateTask() service
    88→- Update modal title and button text based on edit mode
    89→- Test complete edit workflow
    90→
    91→### Phase 3: Integration - Delete Functionality
    92→Implement the delete feature by adding a trash can icon to task cards and creating a confirmation dialog to prevent accidental deletions. Upon confirmation, the task will be removed via the DELETE endpoint.
    93→
    94→- Add delete icon to task cards with click handler
    95→- Create confirmation dialog UI structure
    96→- Implement confirmDelete() method to show confirmation
    97→- Implement deleteTask() method to call service and refresh tasks
    98→- Add delete confirmation state management
    99→- Style confirmation dialog and action icons
   100→- Test complete delete workflow with confirmation
   101→
   102→## Step by Step Tasks
   103→IMPORTANT: Execute every step in order, top to bottom.
   104→
   105→### 1. Add Update and Delete Methods to TaskService
   106→- Open `app/client/src/app/services/task.service.ts`
   107→- After the `createTask()` method (after line 25), add a new method:
   108→  ```typescript
   109→  updateTask(id: number, task: Partial<Omit<Task, 'id' | 'created_at' | 'updated_at'>>): Observable<Task> {
   110→    return this.http.patch<Task>(`${this.apiUrl}/tasks/${id}`, task).pipe(
   111→      catchError(this.handleError)
   112→    );
   113→  }
   114→  ```
   115→- After the `updateTask()` method, add another method:
   116→  ```typescript
   117→  deleteTask(id: number): Observable<void> {
   118→    return this.http.delete<void>(`${this.apiUrl}/tasks/${id}`).pipe(
   119→      catchError(this.handleError)
   120→    );
   121→  }
   122→  ```
   123→- These methods will communicate with the existing backend PATCH and DELETE endpoints
   124→
   125→### 2. Add Edit Mode State to Component
   126→- Open `app/client/src/app/app.component.ts`
   127→- After line 17 (`isModalOpen: boolean = false;`), add new properties:
   128→  ```typescript
   129→  isEditMode: boolean = false;
   130→  editingTaskId: number | null = null;
   131→  isDeleteConfirmOpen: boolean = false;
   132→  taskToDelete: Task | null = null;
   133→  ```
   134→- These properties track whether the modal is in edit mode, which task is being edited, and delete confirmation state
   135→
   136→### 3. Update openModal Method for Create Mode
   137→- In `app/client/src/app/app.component.ts`, modify the `openModal()` method (lines 87-96)
   138→- Update it to explicitly set create mode:
   139→  ```typescript
   140→  openModal(): void {
   141→    this.isModalOpen = true;
   142→    this.isEditMode = false;
   143→    this.editingTaskId = null;
   144→    this.newTask = {
   145→      date: new Date(),
   146→      title: '',
   147→      description: '',
   148→      task_type: 'personal'
   149→    };
   150→    this.formErrors = [];
   151→  }
   152→  ```
   153→
   154→### 4. Add openEditModal Method for Edit Mode
   155→- In `app/client/src/app/app.component.ts`, after the `openModal()` method, add a new method:
   156→  ```typescript
   157→  openEditModal(task: Task): void {
   158→    this.isModalOpen = true;
   159→    this.isEditMode = true;
   160→    this.editingTaskId = task.id;
   161→
   162→    // Convert day_of_week back to a date within the current week
   163→    const dayIndex = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
   164→      .indexOf(task.day_of_week);
   165→    const monday = this.getMonday(new Date());
   166→    const taskDate = new Date(monday);
   167→    taskDate.setDate(monday.getDate() + dayIndex);
   168→
   169→    this.newTask = {
   170→      date: taskDate,
   171→      title: task.title,
   172→      description: task.description || '',
   173→      task_type: task.task_type
   174→    };
   175→    this.formErrors = [];
   176→  }
   177→  ```
   178→
   179→### 5. Update closeModal to Reset Edit State
   180→- In `app/client/src/app/app.component.ts`, modify the `closeModal()` method (lines 98-101)
   181→- Add reset for edit mode state:
   182→  ```typescript
   183→  closeModal(): void {
   184→    this.isModalOpen = false;
   185→    this.isEditMode = false;
   186→    this.editingTaskId = null;
   187→    this.formErrors = [];
   188→  }
   189→  ```
   190→
   191→### 6. Modify onSubmit to Handle Both Create and Edit
   192→- In `app/client/src/app/app.component.ts`, modify the `onSubmit()` method (lines 121-146)
   193→- Update it to detect edit mode and call the appropriate service method:
   194→  ```typescript
   195→  onSubmit(): void {
   196→    if (!this.validateForm()) {
   197→      return;
   198→    }
   199→
   200→    const dayOfWeek = this.getDayOfWeekFromDate(this.newTask.date);
   201→
   202→    const taskData = {
   203→      title: this.newTask.title,
   204→      description: this.newTask.description || null,
   205→      day_of_week: dayOfWeek,
   206→      time_slot: '12:00 PM',
   207→      task_type: this.newTask.task_type,
   208→      completed: false
   209→    };
   210→
   211→    if (this.isEditMode && this.editingTaskId !== null) {
   212→      // Update existing task
   213→      this.taskService.updateTask(this.editingTaskId, taskData).subscribe({
   214→        next: () => {
   215→          this.closeModal();
   216→          this.loadTasks();
   217→        },
   218→        error: (error) => {
   219→          this.formErrors = ['Failed to update task: ' + error.message];
   220→        }
   221→      });
   222→    } else {
   223→      // Create new task
   224→      this.taskService.createTask(taskData).subscribe({
   225→        next: () => {
   226→          this.closeModal();
   227→          this.loadTasks();
   228→        },
   229→        error: (error) => {
   230→          this.formErrors = ['Failed to create task: ' + error.message];
   231→        }
   232→      });
   233→    }
   234→  }
   235→  ```
   236→
   237→### 7. Add Delete Confirmation Methods
   238→- In `app/client/src/app/app.component.ts`, after the `loadTasks()` method, add new methods:
   239→  ```typescript
   240→  openDeleteConfirmation(task: Task): void {
   241→    this.isDeleteConfirmOpen = true;
   242→    this.taskToDelete = task;
   243→  }
   244→
   245→  closeDeleteConfirmation(): void {
   246→    this.isDeleteConfirmOpen = false;
   247→    this.taskToDelete = null;
   248→  }
   249→
   250→  confirmDeleteTask(): void {
   251→    if (this.taskToDelete) {
   252→      this.taskService.deleteTask(this.taskToDelete.id).subscribe({
   253→        next: () => {
   254→          this.closeDeleteConfirmation();
   255→          this.loadTasks();
   256→        },
   257→        error: (error) => {
   258→          console.error('Failed to delete task:', error);
   259→          this.closeDeleteConfirmation();
   260→        }
   261→      });
   262→    }
   263→  }
   264→  ```
